#2021GM-JUL Q03
Pemphigus : flaccid blisters, degradation of intercelluar junctions within epidermis, usually in middle aged.


Blisters can occurs in

  • Viral diseases
    • chickenpox, HFM disease, herpes simplex
  • Bacterial infection
    • Impetigo, cellulitis
  • Inflammatory disorders
    • Eczema, contact dermatitis, insect bite reaction
  • Immunological disorders
    • Hermatitis herpetiformis, pemphigus, pemphigoid, erythema multiforme
  • Metabolic disorders
    • Porphyria

Bullae are large blisters; can occur in certain other condictions.

  • Eg. congenital causes -> epiermolysis bullosa
    The most important ones are
  • Bullous pemphigoid
  • pemphigus
  • dermatitis herpetiformis
  • linear IgA

  • Rare, life threatening

[!INFO] Nikolsky sign
Simple version: top layers of the skin separate from the lower layers.
Complex version:
Lateral pressure applied to the border of a blister causes displacement of the epidermis and extension of the blister.
There is weakening of the assoociation between corneal and granular layers because of breakdown of desmosomes.
Apparently normal skin between the obvious blistering lesions is also affected.
Nikolsky sign is pathognomonic for

  • pemphigus,
  • toxic epidermal necrolysis, and
  • staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome
  • Rarer than pemphigus vulgaris. No oral lesions.
  • Subcorneal blistering is seen.
  • manifests in UV irratidated skin sites.

Bullous pemphigoid

[!TIP] pemphigOid ->
O for

  • Old
  • DermO-epidermoid junction (not intraepidermal - no O's)
  • round Shape of O -> tense
  • O my god it itches!

  • Occurs over 60 years of age.
  • IgG autoantibodies that targer basement membrane cell -> dermo-epidermal junction breakdown -> subepidermal split
  • Tense blisters
  • Steroid and steroid sparing drugs for treatment.
  • No scarring
  • Course: acute of insidious episodes which remit.
  • Severe pruritus.Source
  • Treatment can be stopped after few years but disease often recurs.
  • Can involve mucous membranes (20%).
  • Can be triggered by vaccination (in children) and drugs (NSAIDS, ACEi, frusemide)
  • Pemphigoid gestationalis is rare and occurs in the latter half of #pregnancy (T2 and T3) and post partum.

Mucous membrane pemphigoid - cicatrical pemphigoid

Involves painful sores mouth, nasal and genital mucosa.

  • Linear IgA deposition along the dermo-epidermal junction
  • Cause not know. Associated with vancomycin, ampicillin and amiodarone.
  • chronic tense bullae.
  • Lesions show string of jewels/ beads appearance as blisters are seen around the periphery of the lesion or bullae or in clusters (jewel sign)
  • Mucous membranes are commonly involved.
  • Limbs and trunk most affected in adults. Children: Lower abdomen and perineum.
  • Treatment: dapsone and slphaphyridine for persistent symtoms)
  • Puritus is common


    Cutaneous manifestation of [[2021-SBR-November#Coeliac disease|coeliac disease]].
    IgA deposition in papillary dermis.
    Subepidermal blisters with neutrophil infiltrae causing microsabscesses.
    Intermittent lesions.
    Mainly a rash with small blisters often scratched away due to the pruritus.
    Mainly affects knees, elbows and buttocks.
    Intensely pruritic.
    Treatmetn: lifelong avoidance of gluten + (dapsone and slphaphyridine for persistent symtoms)

Geriatric medicine

[!INFO] The main questions in geriatric medicine - Kumar and Clark
In Geriatric medicine, a balance has to be found between

  1. What can be done for the patient and
  2. What should be done for the patient.
    • Edmunt Pellegrino

Common problems in geriatric medicine are

  • Frailty - #2021GM-JUL Q02
    decreased physiological reserve of the organ systems. In a frail person, a given physiological stress will have a greater negative impact on the organ systems.

    • Frailty does not necessarily correspond with age; it is possible to be young and frail and elderly and not frail. eg: fit person -> uti -> minimal symptoms.
    • frail person -> uti -> delerium etc.
    • Therefore, a patient must be managed according to their functional status and *not their chronological age.
    • 3 or more of the criteria define the presence of frailty.

  • Sarcopenia: progressive, systemic muscle disorder which leads to loss of muscle fibers, in particular fast twitch fibers.

    • Increased risk of falls and fractures
    • Maximum amount of oxygen consumption (VO2 max) reduces.
    • Gait speed reduces
    • Reduced energy expenditure ensues.
    • This somehow causes an energy deficit (probably due to anorexia of aging)-> not enough ATP for apoptosis -> cells instead undergo necrosis -> Even more ATP is used up -> cycle propagates -> more sarcopenia -> frailty cycle

  • Multimorbidity - presence of two or more medical conditions that may or may not interact.

    • Multimorbidity can lead to prescribing cascades and co prescription (omeprazole added to aspirin therapy)

  • Disability : Physical or mental impairment which has substantial and long term negative impact on the ability of a person to carry out daily activities.

Other common issues in the elderly

  • Polypharmacy
  • Falls
  • Postural hypotension
  • Delirium
  • Urinary Tract infections
  • Urinary incontinence
  • Older adult abuse
  • Rehabilitation
  • Loneliness
  • Complex discharge planning
  • Carer strain

Oxygen delivery

#2021GM-JUL Q04

Nasal canulae:

  • Upto 30% FiO2.
  • Flow up to 4L/min

Hudson mask:

  • To avoid rebreathing, miminum flow rate is 4 L/min. Maximum flow is about 10 L/min.
  • 30-40% oxygem (note : minimum is 30%)

NRBM:

  • Requires 15 L flow rate
  • NRBM Fi02 is 60-90% FiO2; Not 100 because of valve leaks and leaks surrounding mask.
  • Apparently, denirogenation can lead to atelectasis Source

HFNO:

  • Flow rate up to 60 L/min
  • FiO2 21 - 100%.
- High Hepcidin reduces iron deposition in RET. Therefore, in HH, iron deposition occurs first in parenchymal tissue and then in RET. (opposite of *transfusional* iron overload).
- ?Pancreas is spared in haemosiderosis.
  • Low hepcidin causes increased intestinal absorption of iron.
    • Hepicidin 'hold' iron at bay.

"Bacterial Helped Tropical Cows Reject Wild Radical Parasites."

  • The disease process results in crypt hyperplasia and villous atrophy.
  • Increased risk of small bowel lymphoma.
  • Malabsorption can cause iron defieciency and folate deficiency.
